# PHASE 10 — FALCO RUNTIME SECURITY & THREAT DETECTION

[## [SECTION: Step 11 — The Falco Threat Model]]

1
03:52:06,000 --> 03:52:12,000
Now let's move to Phase 10. Falco runtime security and threat detection.
This is the final security layer.

2
03:52:12,000 --> 03:52:18,000
Before installing anything, understand what Falco detects and why it matters.
For a financial RAG agent specifically.

3
03:52:18,000 --> 03:52:24,000
Your application runs LLM inference, reads sensitive financial data from SEC filings.
And holds database credentials in Vault-injected files.

4
03:52:24,000 --> 03:52:30,000
The realistic attack scenarios are.

5
03:52:30,000 --> 03:52:36,000
Attacker gets RCE via prompt injection, spawns a shell.
Falco detects shell spawned in financial RAG pod.

6
03:52:36,000 --> 03:52:42,000
Malware reads slash vault slash secrets slash database.env.
Falco detects Vault secret read by unexpected process.

7
03:52:42,000 --> 03:52:48,000
Compromised agent pod connects to attacker's command and control server.
Falco detects unexpected outbound connection.

8
03:52:48,000 --> 03:52:54,000
Attacker uses kubectl exec to enter a pod.
Falco detects kubectl exec in financial RAG namespace.

9
03:52:54,000 --> 03:53:00,000
Cryptojacking. attacker runs mining software.
Falco detects crypto mining in financial RAG.

10
03:53:00,000 --> 03:53:06,000
Container escape. writes to read-only filesystem.
Falco detects write outside allowed paths.

11
03:53:06,000 --> 03:53:12,000
Privilege escalation via setuid binary.
Falco detects privilege escalation in financial RAG pod.

12
03:53:12,000 --> 03:53:18,000
Credential harvesting via proc star star environ.
Falco detects read process environment.

13
03:53:18,000 --> 03:53:24,000
Falco detects these at the syscall layer.
Below the application, below the container runtime.

14
03:53:24,000 --> 03:53:30,000
Even if the attacker has full control of the Python process.
Falco sees the underlying open, connect, and execve syscalls.


[## [SECTION: Step 12 — Install Falco (Component #121)]]


15
03:53:30,000 --> 03:53:36,000
Now let's install Falco using Helm.

16
03:53:36,000 --> 03:53:42,000
Add the FalcoSecurity repo, create the falco namespace.
Falco runs in kube-system, not the falco namespace.

17
03:53:42,000 --> 03:53:48,000
Why kube-system? Falco runs as a DaemonSet that must access the host's eBPF subsystem.
Running it in kube-system ensures it starts early and has the required privileges.

18
03:53:48,000 --> 03:53:54,000
Install with eBPF driver and Falcosidekick.
The Helm chart creates its own service account with minimum permissions.

19
03:53:54,000 --> 03:54:00,000
Now verify Falco is running.

20
03:54:00,000 --> 03:54:06,000
Check Falco pods are running on all nodes.
kubectl get pods in kube-system with the Falco label.

21
03:54:06,000 --> 03:54:12,000
Check eBPF probe loaded.
kubectl exec and look for falco directory in the BPF filesystem.

22
03:54:12,000 --> 03:54:18,000
List loaded rules.
kubectl exec with falco minus l and grep for financial-rag.

23
03:54:18,000 --> 03:54:24,000
Our Falco installation is complete.
Now let's add custom rules.


[## [SECTION: Step 13 — Custom Rules (Components #125–131)]]


24
03:54:24,000 --> 03:54:30,000
Now let's create our custom Falco rules.
We'll put them in falco/rules/financial_rag_rules.yaml

25
03:54:30,000 --> 03:54:36,000
Every Falco rule has five parts.
Rule name, description, condition, output, priority, and MITRE tags.

26
03:54:36,000 --> 03:54:42,000
The condition is a boolean expression using Falco fields.
It looks for specific system calls and matches them to labels.

27
03:54:42,000 --> 03:54:48,000
First, define macros for reusable conditions.
financial_rag_namespace condition checks namespace equals financial-rag.

28
03:54:48,000 --> 03:54:54,000
api_container condition checks namespace and component label equals api.
agent_container condition checks namespace and component label equals agent.

29
03:54:54,000 --> 03:55:00,000
ingestion_container condition checks namespace and component label equals ingestion.
vault_agent_container condition checks container name equals vault-agent.

30
03:55:00,000 --> 03:55:06,000
istio_proxy_container condition checks container name equals istio-proxy.
allowed_containers combines vault-agent, istio-proxy, api, agent, and ingestion.

31
03:55:06,000 --> 03:55:12,000
Rule one. Shell spawned in financial-rag pod.
This should never happen in production.

32
03:55:12,000 --> 03:55:18,000
The condition checks for a spawned process, in the financial-rag namespace.
And the process name matches a shell like bash or sh.

33
03:55:18,000 --> 03:55:24,000
It excludes the vault-agent and istio-proxy containers.
They have legitimate reasons to spawn subprocesses.

34
03:55:24,000 --> 03:55:30,000
Priority is CRITICAL. If a shell appears, page someone immediately.

35
03:55:30,000 --> 03:55:36,000
Rule two. Unexpected outbound connection from agent pod.

36
03:55:36,000 --> 03:55:42,000
The condition checks for outbound traffic from the agent container.
And the destination port is NOT in the allowed list.

37
03:55:42,000 --> 03:55:48,000
Allowed ports are 5432 for PostgreSQL, 6379 for Redis.
443 for HTTPS, and 15001 and 15006 for Istio.

38
03:55:48,000 --> 03:55:54,000
This catches Cilium policy bypass attempts.
Even if an attacker bypasses the network policy, Falco still alerts.

39
03:55:54,000 --> 03:56:00,000
Rule three. Write to filesystem outside allowed paths.

40
03:56:00,000 --> 03:56:06,000
All containers have readOnlyRootFilesystem set to true.
Only slash tmp and slash vault slash secrets should be writable.

41
03:56:06,000 --> 03:56:12,000
If a process writes anywhere else, something is wrong.
This catches container escape attempts.

42
03:56:12,000 --> 03:56:18,000
Rule four. Vault secret read by unexpected process.

43
03:56:18,000 --> 03:56:24,000
This is critical for your security model.
The condition checks for a process reading from slash vault slash secrets.

44
03:56:24,000 --> 03:56:30,000
And the process name is NOT python3, uvicorn, gunicorn, or vault.
If a shell reads database.env, Falco fires immediately.

45
03:56:30,000 --> 03:56:36,000
Rule five. Privilege escalation attempt.
Executing a setuid or setgid binary inside a financial-rag pod.

46
03:56:36,000 --> 03:56:42,000
Rule six. Crypto mining detection.
Known miner process names like xmrig or ethminer.

47
03:56:42,000 --> 03:56:48,000
Rule seven. kubectl exec into a financial-rag pod.
Priority is WARNING, not CRITICAL. Exec is allowed, but must be logged.

48
03:56:48,000 --> 03:56:54,000
Rule eight. Read process environment.
Someone reading slash proc slash star slash environ, harvesting credentials.

49
03:56:54,000 --> 03:57:00,000
Our custom rules are complete.
Eight rules covering the financial RAG threat model.


[## [SECTION: Step 14 — Deploy Rules as ConfigMap (Component #132)]]


50
03:57:00,000 --> 03:57:06,000
Now deploy these rules as a ConfigMap.

51
03:57:06,000 --> 03:57:12,000
Create the ConfigMap from the rules file.
kubectl create configmap from-file.

52
03:57:12,000 --> 03:57:18,000
The Helm values mount this ConfigMap into Falco's rules directory.
To update rules without restarting, send SIGHUP to the Falco process.

53
03:57:18,000 --> 03:57:24,000
Update the ConfigMap and then send kill dash 1 to the Falco process.
This reloads rules without restarting the daemon.

54
03:57:24,000 --> 03:57:30,000
Our rules ConfigMap is complete.
Falco now has custom rules for financial-rag.


[## [SECTION: Step 15 — Test Rules (Component #134)]]


55
03:57:30,000 --> 03:57:36,000
Now let's test each rule in a non-production namespace.

56
03:57:36,000 --> 03:57:42,000
Test one. Shell spawn detection.
Create a test pod with the api component label.

57
03:57:42,000 --> 03:57:48,000
kubectl run test-shell with image alpine.
Labels app.kubernetes.io/component equals api.

58
03:57:48,000 --> 03:57:54,000
Then exec into the pod and run bin slash sh.
kubectl exec test-shell dash dash bin slash sh dash c echo test.

59
03:57:54,000 --> 03:58:00,000
Check Falco logs for Shell Spawned in Financial RAG Pod.
Expected priority CRITICAL.

60
03:58:00,000 --> 03:58:06,000
Test two. Vault secret read.
kubectl exec test-shell dash dash cat slash vault slash secrets slash database.env.

61
03:58:06,000 --> 03:58:12,000
Expected alert. Vault Secret Read by Unexpected Process with priority CRITICAL.

62
03:58:12,000 --> 03:58:18,000
Test three. Outbound connection to unexpected port.
kubectl exec test-shell dash dash wget to example.com on port 8080.

63
03:58:18,000 --> 03:58:24,000
Expected alert. Unexpected Outbound Connection with priority HIGH.

64
03:58:24,000 --> 03:58:30,000
Clean up the test pod.
kubectl delete pod test-shell.

65
03:58:30,000 --> 03:58:36,000
Our rules are tested and working.
Falco detects all critical attack patterns.


[## [SECTION: Step 16 — Falcosidekick (Components #136–138)]]


66
03:58:36,000 --> 03:58:42,000
Now let's configure Falcosidekick.
Falcosidekick routes Falco alerts to external destinations.

67
03:58:42,000 --> 03:58:48,000
Three destinations configured.

68
03:58:48,000 --> 03:58:54,000
Slack for warnings and above.
The webhook URL is injected via set at install time.

69
03:58:54,000 --> 03:59:00,000
The message format includes the rule name, priority, and pod name.
PagerDuty for CRITICAL only, wakes someone up.

70
03:59:00,000 --> 03:59:06,000
CloudWatch for all events, SOC2 audit trail.
The log group is slash aws slash falco slash financial-rag.

71
03:59:06,000 --> 03:59:12,000
Two replicas with pod anti-affinity ensures alert delivery.
Even if one node fails, the other continues.

72
03:59:12,000 --> 03:59:18,000
Install Falcosidekick with Helm upgrade.
Use the falco-helm-values.yaml and falcosidekick-values.yaml.

73
03:59:18,000 --> 03:59:24,000
Set falcosidekick.config.slack.webhookurl and pagerduty routingkey.

74
03:59:24,000 --> 03:59:30,000
Verify Falcosidekick is receiving events.
Port-forward to the UI and open localhost 2802.

75
03:59:30,000 --> 03:59:36,000
Our Falcosidekick configuration is complete.
Alerts now route to Slack, PagerDuty, and CloudWatch.


[## [SECTION: Step 17 — Prometheus Integration (Components #144–146)]]


76
03:59:36,000 --> 03:59:42,000
Now let's integrate Falco with Prometheus.

77
03:59:42,000 --> 03:59:48,000
Falco exposes metrics at slash metrics.
The Helm values enable the ServiceMonitor automatically.

78
03:59:48,000 --> 03:59:54,000
Three Prometheus security alerts.

79
03:59:54,000 --> 04:00:00,000
Alert one. FalcoCriticalEventDetected.
expr sums the rate of falco_events_total with priority Critical.

80
04:00:00,000 --> 04:00:06,000
for 0m means fire immediately with zero stabilization period.
Security events at CRITICAL priority require immediate response.

81
04:00:06,000 --> 04:00:12,000
Alert two. CiliumDropRateHigh.
expr sums the rate of hubble_drop_total in the financial-rag namespace.

82
04:00:12,000 --> 04:00:18,000
If drop rate exceeds 10 per second for 2 minutes, fire alert.
Possible lateral movement attempt.

83
04:00:18,000 --> 04:00:24,000
Alert three. VaultTokenRenewalFailure.
expr sums the rate of financial_rag_vault_token_renewal_errors_total.

84
04:00:24,000 --> 04:00:30,000
If token renewal fails for 1 minute, secrets will expire.
Fire alert.

85
04:00:30,000 --> 04:00:36,000
Apply the Prometheus alerts.
kubectl apply with the financial-rag-alerts.yaml file.

86
04:00:36,000 --> 04:00:42,000
Our Prometheus integration is complete.
Falco metrics are now alertable.


[## [SECTION: Step 18 — Gitleaks Standalone Workflow]]


87
04:00:42,000 --> 04:00:48,000
Now let's look at the standalone gitleaks workflow.
It runs separately from the main CI pipeline.

88
04:00:48,000 --> 04:00:54,000
Place it at .github/workflows/gitleaks.yml.

89
04:00:54,000 --> 04:01:00,000
Two important features beyond the basic gitleaks check.

90
04:01:00,000 --> 04:01:06,000
First, weekly full-history scan.
The scheduled run uses fetch-depth zero, full history.

91
04:01:06,000 --> 04:01:12,000
This catches secrets buried in old commits.
Not just the latest 50. Secrets that were deleted six months ago but are still in the git object store.

92
04:01:12,000 --> 04:01:18,000
Second, PR comment on detection.
When a secret is found in a PR, a comment is posted.

93
04:01:18,000 --> 04:01:24,000
With exact remediation steps.
Rotate the credential, use git-filter-repo to remove from history.

94
04:01:24,000 --> 04:01:30,000
Developers get actionable instructions in the PR.
Not just a failed check.

95
04:01:30,000 --> 04:01:36,000
Third, Slack alert.
The security channel gets notified immediately.

96
04:01:36,000 --> 04:01:42,000
Not just the developer who pushed.
The security team sees every detection even if the developer dismisses the PR check.

97
04:01:42,000 --> 04:01:48,000
Our gitleaks standalone workflow is complete.
Secret scanning is now comprehensive.


